Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

1:27 PM Prosecuting attorney Chad C La Lor in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Alicia Kay Robinson appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Ryan Anthony Reid in court for Alicia Kay Robinson. Defendant's address confirmed. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, enters pleas of not guilty to the misdemeanor count(s), and requests a preliminary hearing. State asks for $2500 cash bail. No use or possession of a controlled substance or drug-related paraphernalia without a valid prescription. State indicates that the defendant is currently on Extended Supervision and has a hold. Recites defendant's prior criminal convictions in WI and MN and defendant's FTAs.  Attorney Reid indicates the defendant is a local resident, has employment in Duluth with family and a child in the area. Asks for $500 cash bond. Notes FTAs are dated. Court notes concerns over defendant's FTAs and being on ES while alleged to have committed another felony. Defendant makes statement to the court. 

Court orders $2500 cash. No use or possession of a controlled substance or drug-related paraphernalia without a valid prescription.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for July 13, 2022 at 11:45 am.
Status conference scheduled for July 11, 2022 at 03:00 pm.
